central players in what he calls the social health matrix, which can serve both healthy children and those with special needs. He also outlines how schools, healthcare facilities, religious groups, and other organizations can help dads make a positive imprint on their families’ health, fitness, and well-being. Anchored in compelling life stories of joy, tragedy, and resilience, Dads, Kids, and Fitness extends and deepens public conversation about health at a pivotal historical moment. Its progressive message breathes new life into discussions about fathering, manhood, and health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamiliesxHealth and hygiene. 0aFather and child. 0aHealth. 0aPhysical fitness. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  ahealth, family, father, parent, parenting, exercise, fitness, fit, nutrition, children, child, health care, diet, habit, health conscious, raising kids, raising children, dads, family health, fathering.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358488140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813584881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813584881.jpg  a978-3-11-066614-4  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK